[1]
Date: Fri, 25 Feb 2005 09:52:14 -0000
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Atlanta Journal-Constitution [edited]
<http://www.ajc.com/news/content/news/stories/0205/25polio.html>

Polio virus resurfaces in Ethiopia: vaccination drive targets 100 million
----------------------------------
A child in Ethiopia has been diagnosed with polio, marking that country's
1st case in 4 years and dealing a further setback to plans to eradicate the
disease, international health authorities said on Thursday. The discovery
makes Ethiopia the 14th country to experience a resurgence of the disease
since polio began to spread from northern Nigeria in mid-2003 after several
provinces suspended vaccination.
The World Health Organization and the United Nations Childrens' Fund
announced the Ethiopian case on Thursday as authorities prepared for an
immunization drive in 22 African countries beginning on Saturday that aims
to inoculate 100 million children.
Because genetic fingerprinting has not been completed, the WHO was not able
to say with certainty that the polio virus affecting the child in Ethiopia
is the same strain that leaked from northern Nigeria when provinces there
ceased vaccinating from mid-2003 to mid-2004. "But it can't just have
appeared," said Oliver Rosenbauer of the WHO's polio eradication program.
"We assume it is part of the ongoing epidemic."
Health authorities greeted the news with dismay because every recognized
case signals the existence of a silent epidemic: For every child paralyzed
by polio, there are usually up to 200 more who do not show symptoms but can
still spread the virus to others [the range of paralysis to infected ratio
observed in polio epidemics is 1 in 50 to 1 in 1000 - Mod.MPP]. In
addition, many of the countries where polio still exists lack the
scientific capacity to confirm its presence, so tests must be sent to labs
in the developed world for confirmation -- and in the weeks or months it
takes for infections to be confirmed, the disease can spread.
Since the Nigerian suspension of vaccination, polio has flared up in 12
additional African countries, from Guinea on the west coast to Sudan on the
east coast, as well as in Saudi Arabia, where one case was found in
November [2004] and another in December [2004] during the annual visit of 2
million religious pilgrims.
All of those countries had earlier been declared polio-free. In 4 of them
-- Burkina Faso, Chad, Cote d'Ivoire and the Sudan -- polio has begun
passing from person to person again, say health officials. In Sudan, where
polio eradication efforts are disrupted by civil unrest, there have been
125 cases of the disease since last May [2004].
The international campaign to eradicate polio by 2005 was launched in 1988
at a cost so far of about USD 3 billion. Run by WHO, UNICEF, and the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, the effort is carried out in
the field by Rotary International volunteers.
[Byline: MAJ McKenna]
