[3]
Date: 25 Feb 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Polio eradication website [edited]
<http://www.polioeradication.org/content/pressreleases/PressRelease20050225.doc
>

Coast-to-coast polio drive to counter epidemic in Africa
--------------------------------------------------------
A mass polio immunization drive starting today across Africa gained greater
urgency from reports that a child has contracted polio in Ethiopia, the 1st
case there in 4 years.
The cross-continental drive -- spanning 22 countries and reaching 100
million children -- is the 1st in a series of 2005 campaigns to stamp out
polio in Africa, which saw a fierce resurgence during 2004, endangering
global eradication efforts. With polio now in its low-transmission season,
the next few months are critical to stopping the virus.
Countries joining the campaigns this round include the Democratic Republic
of Congo, Ethiopia, and Eritrea on the southern and eastern edges of the
epidemic. In the west, Cote d'Ivoire is rejoining the effort for the 1st
time since civil unrest halted activities last November [2004], causing
months of concern after the country was re-infected early in the regional
epidemic.
"By reaching children cut off from the eradication effort by insecurity and
the threat of violence, African leaders have a real opportunity to halt
polio's advance," said Dr. Ezio Murzi, UNICEF Regional Director for West
and Central Africa. On the other side of the continent, Sudanese health
officials -- in the wake of the Nairobi peace accord -- are cooperating to
immunize children in both the north and south. Next door, Ethiopia is
concentrating on activities along its northern and western borders, where
the new case was found.
In a reminder of the ease with which the virus travels, 2 recent cases in
Saudi Arabia appear to be related to virus originating in Nigeria and
entering via Sudan. Nigeria accounts for over 60 percent of cases
worldwide. [The 2nd case reported in Saudi Arabia with date of onset in
late December 2004, was reported in ProMED-mail in "Poliomyelitis - Saudi
Arabia: Haj concerns 20050211.0463". At that time there was concern over
poliovirus circulation in Saudi Arabia coincident with the Haj. It has
subsequently been learned that the affected child's household had family
visitors from Nigeria preceding the onset of the child's illness, reducing
the likelihood that the infection was from widespread poliovirus
circulation in Saudi Arabia. - Mod.MPP]
"Eradication in Africa requires not only reaching all children in the
newly-infected areas, but most importantly, immunizing every child in those
countries which have never interrupted transmission -- Nigeria and Niger,"
said WHO Regional Director for Africa Dr Luis Sambo. "It is gratifying to
note that both countries are fully committed to the polio eradication drive."
Health officials say that progress made since the 1st response to the
outbreak in Africa -- massive coordinated immunization campaigns in October
and November 2004 -- has been positive but fragile. Success in the 2nd
phase of this intensified eradication effort, coupled with improved access
to routine immunization, is critical to stopping the epidemic. To finance
the 2005 immunization rounds, USD $75 million is needed by July; some UDS
$200 million will be required in 2006. African leaders have re-doubled
their commitment in the face of the epidemic, as evidenced in recent
declarations at the African Union summit by the AU's top leadership. "Polio
eradication has the unswerving commitment of all Africans -- from leaders
to parents and children themselves," said Marie-Irene Richmond-Ahoua,
Rotary's National PolioPlus Chair for Cote d'Ivoire. Since 1985, Rotary
members have contributed countless volunteer hours and more than USD $500
million to the polio eradication effort
Vaccinators will be delivering vitamin A drops with the polio vaccine in
many places -- an immunity-boosting strategy that has saved an estimated
1.2 million lives over 12 years. Further mass polio vaccination campaigns
in Africa are scheduled for April and May and again late in the year.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[From the most recent case counts available on the polio eradication
website, as of 4 Jan 2005, the 2004 reported cases from Africa included:
Nigeria 786 cases, Sudan 124 (with 1 case reported in 2005), Central
African Republic 30, Niger 25, Chad 23, Cote d'Ivoire 17, Cameroon 13, Mali
18, Burkina Faso 9, Benin 6, Guinea 5, Egypt 1, and Botswana 1.
Readers are reminded that the countries considered endemic for polio in
2003 were Nigeria, Niger and Egypt, and the cases in the other countries
were related to the outbreak in Nigeria
<http://www.polioeradication.org/content/fixed/casecount.shtml>. The cases
in all countries mentioned above except for Niger and Egypt, and the
previously mentioned cases in Saudi Arabia, are all related to the outbreak
in Nigeria.
Information on the genetic profile of the isolate from Ethiopia is still
pending, but it is highly likely it will be related to the currently
circulating Nigeria or Sudan viruses (which are themselves related). The
mention of a suspected 2nd case (in the 2nd newswire) is of concern that
there may be more widespread circulation of poliovirus in the affected
region in Ethiopia.
The unfortunate consequences of the cessation of polio vaccination in
Nigeria for a year (mid-2003 to mid-2004) continue to be felt, with cases
in countries that have previously interrupted polio transmission. The
obvious concerns are the reseeding of poliovirus circulation into countries
with worsening civil unrest, and disrupted health infrastructures that
serve as barriers to provision of routine services. We await further
information on the genetic typing of the virus isolated from this most
recent case in Ethiopia. - Mod.MPP]
